                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 EW/1–1645: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Venezuela</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Corrigan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caracas</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-01-16T17:00:00-04:30"
                            >January 16, 1945—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:19 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>31. Reference Department’s 21, January 12, 3 p.m.<note n="32" xml:id="d1185fn32"
                        >See telegram 43, January 12, 3 p.m., to Lima, and footnote 1, <ref
                            target="#pg_1312">p. 1312</ref>. The telegram pointed out the
                        possibility that those nations not in a state of war with the Axis might not
                        have the opportunity to join the United Nations or participate in the
                        post-war deliberations.</note> I had a conversation with the Foreign
                        Minister<note n="33" xml:id="d1185fn33">Caracciolo Parra-Perez.</note> this
                    morning which lasted over an hour and will be resumed tomorrow after he has
                    talked to President Medina.<note n="34" xml:id="d1185fn34">Gen. Isaias Medina
                        Angarita.</note> Preliminary reaction not unfavorable.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Corrigan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
